            <img src="/newimages/misc/492blueborder.gif" width="492" height="1"><br> 
			
			
			
      <TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="12">
        <TR valign="top"> 
          <TD class="smalltext">
            Racers are quite possibly the pickiest breed of gamer, always striving for the perfect wheel. Well Ladies and Gentlemen, I may have found the (almost?) perfect wheel.          </TD>
        </TR>
      </TABLE>
      <TABLE width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="12">
        <TR> 
          <TD> 
            <P><SPAN class="Headline">
              The Review              </SPAN>
            <P>
              Thrustmaster have been in the game for quite some time, constructing peripherals ever since the Super Nintendo hit the market many moons ago. From first impressions of this wheel Thrustmaster has really done their homework and have included what the racers have been crying out for the past few years. Clawing their way up the ladder against such companies as Microsoft and Mad Catz, they haven&#8217;t had the easiest market to conquer. Have they conquered the steering wheel market with this fine product? You bet they have, read on to find out why.<br />
<br />
As soon as we sat down to use this wheel we could tell it was going to be something special, it has the exact features that the competitors wheels lack. In the box you will receive the wheel and pedals but there are no free games included. With this peripherals high pricepoint some of you may feel ripped off by this, but hey lets be honest most games free with peripherals are old and out of date. Not to mention sending the price of the product skyrocketing and most mad racing fans are sure to have most of the decent racing titles around.<br />
<br />
Thrustmaster have done something every peripheral company should be doing, including support for both USB and serial connections. This allows the user greater freedom of choice. The peripheral can also be used on older machines without USB functionality. Also for people who are continuously running out of USB ports this is a dream come true. Using the gameport connection doesn&#8217;t affect the beauty of this wheel at all. The response time is practically the same and differences are minimal.  Kudos to Thrustmaster for this. <br />
<br />
A feature included with this wheel is the gear stick. It may be a simple back, forward configuration but it makes games such as Sierras Nascar series so much more enjoyable. Also included at the back of the actual wheel are four flippers for the non-conventional formula 1 setup. This works a treat in Grand Prix 3. The addition of the gear stick is an excellent decision except if you live in the southern hemisphere. The stick is on the right hand side of the wheel, it takes time to train your hand but it is well worth it. The actual wheel also contains four buttons and two (Point of View) POV hats. This allows easy exploration of in game menus.<br />
<br />
We were very surprised at the texture of this wheel considering most wheels on the market today are one hundred percent plastic. The texture is of a rubbery material much like what is used on actual car steering wheels, multiplying the realism ten fold. The wheel has a firmly attached clamp-like system. Enabling the wheel to be knocked without taking much damage.<br />
            </P>
          </TD>
        </TR>
      </TABLE>
